node.text:
Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards
–

node.text:
For the first time ever, Italian futurist Giacomo Balla’s former apartment in Rome will be open for public viewing. The exhibition, hosted by the city’s National Museum of 21st Century Art (@museomaxxi), grants visitors access to the artist’s otherwise upper-middle class flat that he, his wife, and his two daughters began transforming in 1929 as an inhabitable canvas of art—painting the walls, designing and building furniture, and creating their own imaginative floor tiles, carpets, upholstery, light fixtures, and dishes. The approach to domestication was odd, to be sure, but Balla walked the walk: His 1915 manifesto, penned in partnership with fellow countryman and painter Fortunado Depero, introduced the concept that living life itself should be a “total work of art.” For more on Casa Balla and the exhibition that celebrates the 150th anniversary of the artist's birth, head to the link in bio.
–

node.text:
For a young family of five—with a new poodle puppy in tow—this revamped timber cottage in Sydney celebrates lively design. “It’s a humble home with little tweaks that make for playfulness,” says Rebekah Clayton, co-principal of local architecture firm @claytonorszaczky. The goal of the reno was to embrace all that made the weatherboard house special while maxing out the floor plan to better suit the family. To start, the interior walls were blown out to make way for an open-plan kitchen and living area, as well as three bedrooms, bathrooms, and a study. The architects also constructed a cantilevered rear addition that sits atop the original structure—with an eye-catching twist. “For each of our projects, we like to have a gizmo—something fun that’s a bit unexpected or that makes the [structure] unique,” explains Clayton. The showstopper in this case is the fixed screen that wraps the building with white aluminum slats, offering high-visual but low-maintenance impact. Behind the screen, oversize glass doors open up to let in fresh breezes without sacrificing shade or privacy. Despite its striking addition and renovation, the Workers House blends in seamlessly with the rest of the neighborhood from the street. Clayton sums it up: “In some ways this house is the opposite of a standout, and that’s what we consider to be its greatest success.” Take a look through the renovated Workers House at the link in bio.

Dubbed the Michigan Loft for its coveted spot overlooking Michigan Avenue in Chicago’s Motor Row district, this transformed space occupies a century-old building initially used for automotive assembly. Before, its 2,250 square feet felt crowded and disjointed—and altogether too raw. Now, a wood platform wraps the living spaces, creating a more intimate scale. "As one enters this dwelling through a low, wood-clad transition zone, the overwhelming feeling of being inside a large industrial room is very much subdued," says architect @vladimir_radutny. Variations in level allow visitors to experience changing vantage points while moving through more defined areas, from the lofted studio space to the kitchen below. The materials used—like black metal and wood—also create a more cohesive home while maintaining the building’s character. Swipe to see the loft pre-reno, and head to the link in bio for the complete tour.

Las Tres Marias—a shared holiday home for three sisters in Spain’s Mont-Roig del Camp—is a striking renovation of a 1960s dwelling that embodies the “courtyard house” character of coastal homes along the Mediterranean. Working in collaboration, architects @bajetgirame and @nicolasburckhardtarchitekten relied on a preexisting wall that lined the property to connect the home to expansive patios. “We sought to create a retreat that is a deliberately ambiguous habitat between the inside and out,” say the architects. While the former layout comprised small, detached spaces, the redesigned 1,292-square-foot residence features living, dining, kitchen, and loggia areas that flow freely under both new and old arches. Take a walk through Las Tres Marias at the link in bio.
—

node.text:
Renovating this Elysian Heights bungalow was all about adapting, both to the L.A. sun and to the home’s pre-existing structure. @productora_df, a Mexico City–based architecture firm, teamed up with Los Angeles’s @part_office to breathe new life into the previously unremarkable 1930s home that now showcases a striking, bright-blue exterior and sawtooth roof, along with generous windows and doors that open onto shaded patios. While maintaining much of the original structure, the architects also affixed three volumes, creating space for a studio-garage and a primary bedroom. "The project takes advantage of the light across the site," says Wonne Ickx (@wonnex), principal of PRODUCTORA. "You see morning sun through the clerestory windows of the sawtooth extension and sunsets through the new patio windows.” In total, the renovation is a study of contrasts: While the exterior is unified by zingy blue metal cladding, the original volume is rendered in a more subdued stucco. “We really tried for the new addition to establish a dialogue with the previously existing house,” says Ickx. Take a peek into the renovation of Casa Nova at the link in bio.

Now up for grabs in Southern New Zealand is a striking contemporary home, set just a 40-minute drive from Queenstown Airport and Lake Wanaka. Completed in 2020, the multi-level residence offers a sprawling open plan, complete with spacious living areas, four bedrooms, three baths, and two oversized, double-bay garages. Its prominent position and extensive glazing allow for ample natural light to be captured throughout the day, plus awe-inspiring mountainous vistas. In search of a quiet getaway that could double as a holiday hub for extended family and friends, a Mexico City couple found a three-and-a-half-acre property in Valle de Bravo, a popular weekend destination two hours from the capital. The couple reached out to architects @javiersanchezcorral and @carloscmar who collaborated on a plan for three “floating monoliths” that rise from the landscape. Inspired by Donald Judd’s minimalist works, the three volumes feature board-formed concrete walls with charred wood accents and strategically placed cutouts to frame views of the surrounding terrain. “Weekend estates should push users to experience life differently from the way they do in the city,” says Sánchez. “Splitting the residence into smaller ‘houses’ creates independence for multiple inhabitants, while walking from one volume to the next allows for contemplation and engagement with the landscape, the weather, and the views.” Tour the commanding, concrete trio when you try Dwell+ at the link in bio.

A dusty-pink facade is only a hint of what’s inside this 18th-century structure. For Sérgio Antunes, cofounder of Lisbon-based @auroraarquitectos, the charming exterior and its rich pigment provided a fascinating starting point for the renovation of the Rose Building—a single-family residence in southern Portugal that he and @furo_architecturestudio turned into five glowing apartments. Throughout are huge swaths of color with unique touches: For example, painted on the ceiling of the central stair is a moody mural of a woman in the style of a fresco, and in one of the unit’s bathrooms, more artwork on the ceiling depicts a mermaid emerging from a swirl of waves. Elsewhere, arched windows, sloped ceilings, ornate moldings, and wooden doors elegantly play off Portuguese marble and patterned ceramic tiles. With the go-ahead from the city, the architects were also able to construct a modern addition at the rear—The Mustard Building—that pairs natural wood partitions with the subdued tones of creamy terrazzo. For more of the dazzling residence-turned-apartment building, head to the link in bio.

After acquiring enough screen time to last a lifetime, tech industry couple Mike Romanowicz and Lizzie Kardon were craving a change of pace. So, the husband and wife headed to the Catskills, fell in love with an 8-acre wooded plot of land, and set out to build a small cabin. “This was an arbitrary challenge for ourselves,” Romanowicz said. “Could we get out of our comfort zone and build something physical?” In testing their limits, they not only designed and constructed their own minimalist getaway, but also came up with a business plan, too. “Having done that project, and given our background, we figured we could make this experience easier for people to follow in our footsteps,” Romanowicz said. @denoutdoors, a do-it-yourself-cabin-company they launched in July of 2020, provides people with a catalog of building plans that include A-frame and barn house designs. With their own 834-square-foot cabin as an example, they’re promoting a “less is more” philosophy—a concept they hope to pass on to those interested in building their own minimalist retreats. Tour the couple’s Catskills cabin, known as Fox Den, at the link in bio.

node.text:
Walls are out. Curtains are up. Acclaimed for their nifty storage tactics and clever spatial arrangements, the architects at @burr.studio have again surpassed small-space expectations. “This time around, we transformed a humble apartment built in the ‘70s into an experimental dwelling,” says the Madrid-based firm. "The independent rooms were strictly compiled, reducing each one’s potential size and function," the architects continue. "Our proposed transformation radically opposed this layout, as we sought to dismantle the divisions between spaces and dissolve the limits of each." Through the use of a central core that integrates the main facilities—note that the toilet can be isolated—tenants are able to build, or break down, spaces as they choose, from a study space to a private bedroom. The curtains themselves are also notable, created from spatially-relevant materials that nod to their function, like a quilted cloth for the bedroom, or a noise-reducing series of felt strips for a home office. In total, these space-saving solutions allow the small-yet-fully-equipped dwelling to effectively serve multiple purposes, all while accommodating modern living. Take a peek behind the curtain at the link in bio.

“This is the cheapest house either of our offices have ever worked on,” say homeowners and architects Ernesto Crangolino and Krista Whitson of @alterstudio and @ml_arch, respectively. At a final construction cost of $550,000—landscaping and a solar array pushed it slightly over budget, but made the home net zero—the couple achieved this svelte four-bedroom in Austin, Texas, that was largely designed out of the circumstances of a constrained lot. “We hate it when architecture is a consequence of forces outside of it,” say the architects, “but it meant that the house had to be very agile and responsive.” Check out the cleverly compact home, included in last year’s @aiaaustin Home Tours, at the link in our bio.

Many can attest to the fact that siblings challenge us in the best ways. This time, architect @pollyharbisondesign, who usually gravitates toward a relaxed minimalism, was tasked by her sister, Margot, with a renovation that embraces color and texture. Luckily, the 1940s home, located in the Sydney suburb of Lindfield, came with inspiration a few steps outside. “Ewen loves these eclectic, crazy, colorful flowers,” Margot says about her husband and the garden that runs parallel to their home. With the help of @arentpykestudio—who added rich textures and finishes, such as the marble that runs from countertop to stairway to checkered floor—Polly was able to strike a balance between old and new. The old home, with only the loss of a small area that’s been repurposed as a brick courtyard, stands nearly untouched next to its accompanying addition that houses a kitchen, living room, primary bedroom, and bathroom that leads directly to an outdoor shower overlooking the greenery. "Despite all this clash of materials and color, the overriding sense of the building is that it’s very calm," Polly says. "It’s got almost a monastic calm feeling to it and it’s all about this lovely green garden." Take a look at the striking, yet serene home at the link in bio.
